Orchestrates the scan pipeline: directory walk, optional model-based summarization, hash tree computation, README generation, and orphan cleanup. Four entry points serve different needs: `scan_run` is the full pipeline (walkâ†’pruneâ†’summarizeâ†’hashâ†’README); `check_run` validates the hash tree against stored sidecars without model calls; `update_run` is pruneâ†’checkâ†’rebuild (deletes orphans, regenerates only stale summaries, persists fresh hashes); `prune_run` is filesystem cleanup alone. `summarize` is the inner generic step, usable directly in tests with in-memory `Fs` and `Agent` fakes.

Prompts are loaded from `prompts_dir` relative to the process cwd, not the scan targetâ€”the target may not carry CTX's prompt files. All four entry points use `StdFs` with the target as root, except `summarize` which is polymorphic over `Fs`. `scan_run`, `update_run`, and `check_run` call `walk_dir(base)` to enumerate targets, then feed them to hash computation; `summarize` is called with pre-computed targets (in `scan_run`) or used standalone. `check_run` and `update_run` share the stale-detection logic: compute current hash tree, load stored sidecars via `hash::load_stored`, call `hash::diff`, then populate `orphan_artifacts` by comparing the filesystem scan against `stale.orphan_leaves`.

`update_run` prunes orphans first, then checks `stale.is_fresh()`; if fresh, returns early without model calls. If regeneration is needed, `regenerate` processes `stale.changed_files` (leaf summaries), removes `stale.orphan_leaves`, and regenerates `stale.stale_dirs` (rollups, already in deepest-first order). `write_readme` is called after summarization in both `scan_run` and `update_run`.